{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775845953324,"sessionID":"ses_287556285ffeHsKwARZDcKnSF6","part":{"id":"prt_d78aacbca001Z8itHZa4mZ3aCt","messageID":"msg_d78aac4020012XZ1Zm5o5h9nRc","sessionID":"ses_287556285ffeHsKwARZDcKnSF6","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_e943c2bf066a45d2900ac885","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Proposal: AR-007 — K8s Reconciler 控制器\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Implement a Kubernetes Reconciler controller in `pkg/workloadmanager` to provide native, declarative lifecycle management for `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter` custom resources. This transforms the current imperative HTTP API into a Kubernetes-native controller pattern that automatically reconciles desired state with actual cluster state.\n6: \n7: ## Purpose\n8: \n9: ### Background\n10: \n11: AR-004 and AR-005/AR-006 provide HTTP API endpoints for creating and managing sandboxes through imperative requests. However, production environments require:\n12: \n13: - **Declarative resource management**: Users define desired state via CRDs, and the controller ensures the cluster matches\n14: - **Automatic reconciliation**: Self-healing when pods crash, configuration drifts, or external changes occur\n15: - **Status synchronization**: Real-time status updates reflecting actual resource state\n16: - **Event-driven updates**: React to cluster events without polling\n17: - **Integration with K8s ecosystem**: Works with kubectl, Helm, ArgoCD, and other native tools\n18: \n19: ### Goal\n20: \n21: Provide a production-ready Kubernetes controller that:\n22: - Watches AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs and reconciles them to desired state\n23: - Automatically creates/updates/deletes underlying Pods, Services, ConfigMaps, and PVCs\n24: - Emits status conditions reflecting actual resource state\n25: - Handles requeues and exponential backoff for transient failures\n26: - Supports finalizers for graceful deletion\n27: \n28: ### Value\n29: - Enables GitOps workflows for sandbox management\n30: - Self-healing and idempotent operations\n31: - Unified Kubernetes-native management interface\n32: - Reduced operational complexity through automation\n33: \n34: ---\n35: \n36: ## Scope\n37: \n38: ### In-Scope\n39: \n40: | Deliverable | Description |\n41: |-------------|-------------|\n42: | Controller Implementation | core reconciler logic for AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter |\n43: | Informer Integration | Using client-go informers for event-driven reconciliation |\n44: | Resource Provisioning | Pod, Service, ConfigMap, PVC creation from CR specs |\n45: | Status Reconciliation | Update CR status with current state and conditions |\n46: | Requeue Logic | Exponential backoff for failed reconciliations |\n47: | Finalizer Management | Graceful deletion with resource cleanup |\n48: | Unit Tests | Controller logic coverage >60% |\n49: \n50: ### Code Structure\n51: \n52: ```\n53: pkg/workloadmanager/\n54: ├── server.go                           # HTTP server (existing)\n55: ├── service.go                          # WorkloadManager interface (existing)\n56: ├── types.go                            # API types (existing)\n57: ├── client.go                           # Kubernetes client (existing)\n58: ├── controller/\n59: │   ├── controller.go                   # Main controller setup\n60: │   ├── reconciler.go                   # Reconciler implementation\n61: │   ├── agentruntime_reconciler.go    # AgentRuntime-specific logic\n62: │   ├── codeinterpreter_reconciler.go # CodeInterpreter-specific logic\n63: │   ├── builder.go                     # Builder pattern for controller\n64: │   ├── finalizers.go                  # Finalizer management\n65: │   └── status.go                      # Status condition updates\n66: ├── reconciler/\n67: │   ├── pod.go                         # Pod creation/management\n68: │   ├── service.go                    # Service creation/management\n69: │   ├── configmap.go                  # ConfigMap creation/management\n70: │   └── pvc.go                        # PVC creation/management\n71: └── events/\n72:     ├── recorder.go                    # Event recording\n73:     └── events.go                      # Event types\n74: ```\n75: \n76: ### API Changes\n77: \n78: The controller operates on existing CRDs without new API endpoints. However, it enhances the behavior of existing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources:\n79: \n80: #### Status Conditions\n81: \n82: The controller populates these status conditions:\n83: \n84: | Condition | Status | Reason | Description |\n85: |-----------|--------|--------|-------------|\n86: | Initialized | True/False | Initialized | CRD schema validated |\n87: | PodCreated | True/False | PodCreated | Pod resource created |\n88: | Ready | True/False | Ready | All resources ready |\n89: | Failed | True/False | Reason | Reconciliation failed |\n90: \n91: ### Out-of-Scope\n92: - Webhook admission controllers (future enhancement)\n93: - Multi-cluster reconciliation (future enhancement)\n94: - Custom metrics server (separate observability module)\n95: - Horizontal pod autoscaling (separate feature)\n96: \n97: ---\n98: \n99: ## Impact Analysis\n100: \n101: ### Dependencies\n102: \n103: | Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n104: |------------|--------|---------|\n105: | github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go | local | Kubernetes typed client |\n106: | github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/workloadmanager | local | Existing WorkloadManager |\n107: | github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1 | local | AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter types |\n108: | k8s.io/controller-runtime/pkg/controller | ^0.20 | Controller base |\n109: | k8s.io/controller-runtime/pkg/client | ^0.20 | Client interface |\n110: | k8s.io/client-go/informers | ^0.34 | Cached watch support |\n111: | k8s.io/client-go/tools/cache | ^0.34 | Informer handlers |\n112: \n113: ### Upstream Dependencies\n114: \n115: - **AR-004 WorkloadManager HTTP Service Framework** — Provides HTTP server infrastructure\n116: - **AR-005/AR-006 Sandbox Creation/Deletion** — Controller manages resources created by these\n117: - **client-go library** — Generated typed clients for runtime/v1alpha1\n118: \n119: ### Downstream Consumers\n120: \n121: 1. **Kubernetes Controller Manager** — Runs the controller as part of control plane\n122: 2. **kubectl users** — See status of AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter resources\n123: 3. **GitOps tools** — ArgoCD, Flux for declarative sandbox management\n124: 4. **Monitoring systems** — Consume status conditions for alerting\n125: \n126: ### Risks\n127: \n128: | Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n129: |------|----------|------------|\n130: | Resource conflicts | High | OwnerReferences for cascading deletion |\n131: | Memory leaks | Medium | Proper informer teardown, client caching |\n132: | Reconcile loops | Medium | Requeue limits, predicate filtering |\n133: | Status race conditions | Medium | Optimistic locking via resourceVersion |\n134: | Partial failure | Medium | Transactional updates, status last update |\n135: \n136: ---\n137: \n138: ## Alternatives Considered\n139: \n140: ### Option 1: Controller-runtime Based Controller (Selected)\n141: \n142: **Approach**: Use `controller-runtime` library to implement a Kubernetes controller.\n143: \n144: **Pros**:\n145: - Well-established patterns for K8s controllers\n146: - Built-in informer caching and leader election\n147: - Integrates with kubebuilder for deployment\n148: - Familiar to Kubernetes developers\n149: \n150: **Cons**:\n151: - Additional dependency on controller-runtime\n152: - Learning curve for existing team\n153: \n154: **Decision**: Selected — provides the most robust and production-tested approach.\n155: \n156: ---\n157: \n158: ### Option 2: Custom Controller with client-go\n159: \n160: **Approach**: Build a custom controller using raw client-go informers without controller-runtime.\n161: \n162: **Pros**:\n163: - No additional dependencies\n164: - Fine-grained control over reconciliation logic\n165: \n166: **Cons**:\n167: - Reinventing caching, leader election, metrics\n168: - Higher maintenance burden\n169: \n170: **Decision**: Rejected — unnecessary complexity for this use case.\n171: \n172: ---\n173: \n174: ### Option 3: Operator SDK\n175: \n176: **Approach**: Use Operator SDK to scaffold and build the controller.\n177: \n178: **Pros**:\n179: - Complete scaffolding and boilerplate\n180: - Built-in CLI for deployment\n181: - Integration with OLM\n182: \n183: **Cons**:\n184: - Heavyweight for this use case\n185: - Additional abstraction layer\n186: \n187: **Decision**: Rejected — controller-runtime provides sufficient abstraction without full Operator SDK overhead.\n188: \n189: ---\n190: \n191: ### Option 4: External Controller Service\n192: \n193: **Approach**: Implement controller as a separate microservice not embedded in workloadmanager.\n194: \n195: **Pros**:\n196: - Independent scaling and deployment\n197: \n198: **Cons**:\n199: - Additional infrastructure\n200: - Network overhead for client-go communication\n201: - Duplicated code with existing workloadmanager\n202: \n203: **Decision**: Rejected — tightly coupling with workloadmanager provides better resource sharing and simpler deployment.\n204: \n205: ---\n206: \n207: ## Implementation Plan\n208: \n209: ### Phase 1: Controller Foundation\n210: - [ ] Add controller-runtime dependency to go.mod\n211: - [ ] Create controller.go with controller manager setup\n212: - [ ] Implement Builder pattern for controller registration\n213: - [ ] Add predicate filters for namespace/type selection\n214: \n215: ### Phase 2: AgentRuntime Reconciler\n216: - [ ] Implement AgentRuntimeReconciler struct\n217: - [ ] Reconcile() method with resource lookup and diff\n218: - [ ] Pod creation from AgentRuntimeSpec\n219: - [ ] Service creation for TargetPorts\n220: - [ ] Status condition updates\n221: \n222: ### Phase 3: CodeInterpreter Reconciler\n223: - [ ] Implement CodeInterpreterReconciler struct\n224: - [ ] Container template processing\n225: - [ ] Warm pool management\n226: - [ ] Auth mode handling\n227: \n228: ### Phase 4: Resource Management\n229: - [ ] Implement Pod/ReplicaSet management\n230: - [ ] Implement Service management\n231: - [ ] Implement ConfigMap management\n232: - [ ] Implement PVC management for storage\n233: \n234: ### Phase 5: Advanced Features\n235: - [ ] Add finalizers for graceful deletion\n236: - [ ] Implement exponential backoff requeue\n237: - [ ] Add event recording\n238: - [ ] Implement ownerReference for cascading deletion\n239: \n240: ### Phase 6: Testing\n241: - [ ] Unit tests for reconciler logic\n242: - [ ] Mock tests for K8s client interactions\n243: - [ ] Integration tests with mock API server\n244: - [ ] Chaos testing for reconcile loops\n245: \n246: ---\n247: \n248: ## Acceptance Criteria\n249: \n250: - [ ] Controller starts and watches AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter resources\n251: - [ ] Creating AgentRuntime triggers Pod/Service creation\n252: - [ ] Updating AgentRuntime spec triggers resource update\n253: - [ ] Deleting AgentRuntime triggers resource cleanup with finalizer\n254: - [ ] Status conditions accurately reflect resource state\n255: - [ ] Reconcile fails gracefully with proper error handling\n256: - [ ] Controller handles namespace-scoped resources correctly\n257: - [ ] Events are recorded for key lifecycle operations\n258: - [ ] Unit tests pass with >60% coverage\n259: - [ ] Controller integrates with existing workloadmanager deployment\n\n(End of file - total 259 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Proposal: AR-007 — K8s Reconciler 控制器\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement a Kubernetes Reconciler controller in `pkg/workloadmanager` to provide native, declarative lifecycle management for `AgentRuntime` and `CodeInterpreter` custom resources. This transforms the current imperative HTTP API into a Kubernetes-native controller pattern that automatically reconciles desired state with actual cluster state.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nAR-004 and AR-005/AR-006 provide HTTP API endpoints for creating and managing sandboxes through imperative requests. However, production environments require:\n\n- **Declarative resource management**: Users define desired state via CRDs, and the controller ensures the cluster matches\n- **Automatic reconciliation**: Self-healing when pods crash, configuration drifts, or external changes occur\n- **Status synchronization**: Real-time status updates reflecting actual resource state\n- **Event-driven updates**: React to cluster events without polling\n- **Integration with K8s ecosystem**: Works with kubectl, Helm, ArgoCD, and other native tools\n\n### Goal\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775845953314,"end":1775845953322}}}}
