{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775845955155,"sessionID":"ses_287556285ffeHsKwARZDcKnSF6","part":{"id":"prt_d78aad650001v5zDsSEzSXJn11","messageID":"msg_d78aacf5c001Fr6iAX4vnlf3x3","sessionID":"ses_287556285ffeHsKwARZDcKnSF6","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775845986670,"sessionID":"ses_287556285ffeHsKwARZDcKnSF6","part":{"id":"prt_d78aae197001D6ixk3iPwJdmnT","messageID":"msg_d78aacf5c001Fr6iAX4vnlf3x3","sessionID":"ses_287556285ffeHsKwARZDcKnSF6","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_0de79590d60441ceb318de26","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Proposal: AR-008 — Sandbox GC 定时清理机制\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement a scheduled garbage collection (GC) mechanism in `pkg/workloadmanager` to automatically clean up stale, expired, or orphaned sandbox resources managed by the AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter controllers. This ensures resource efficiency and prevents storage/memory leaks from accumulating unused sandboxes.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nThe AR-007 controller creates and manages sandboxes (Pods, Services, PVCs) based on AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs. In production environments:\n\n- **Stale resources accumulate**: Sandboxes that complete execution or exceed time limits remain in the cluster\n- **Resource exhaustion**: Orphaned PVCs, ConfigMaps, and Services consume cluster resources\n- **Manual cleanup is error-prone**: Operators must track and delete resources manually\n- **Compliance requirements**: Data retention policies require automatic cleanup of sensitive workloads\n\n### Goal\n\nProvide an automated GC mechanism that:\n- Periodically scans for expired or stale sandboxes based on TTL policies\n- Cleans up associated resources (Pods, Services, PVCs, ConfigMaps)\n- Updates CR status to reflect GC state\n- Supports configurable cleanup policies per namespace or resource type\n- Integrates with the existing controller for consistent lifecycle management\n\n### Value\n- Prevents resource accumulation and cluster bloat\n- Automates compliance with data retention policies\n- Reduces operational overhead for sandbox management\n- Improves cluster stability by reclaiming compute and storage resources\n\n---\n\n## Scope\n\n### In-Scope\n\n| Deliverable | Description |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| GC Controller | Background controller for periodic cleanup scanning |\n| TTL Policy Engine | Evaluate time-based expiration for sandbox resources |\n| Resource Cleanup | Delete associated Pods, Services, PVCs, ConfigMaps |\n| Finalizer Integration | Coordinate with AR-007 finalizers for graceful cleanup |\n| Configuration | TTL defaults, namespace filters, cleanup interval |\n| Metrics | GC execution counts, cleanup latency, resource freed |\n| Unit Tests | GC logic coverage >60% |\n\n### Code Structure\n\n```\npkg/workloadmanager/\n├── server.go                           # HTTP server (existing)\n├── service.go                          # WorkloadManager interface (existing)\n├── types.go                            # API types (existing)\n├── client.go                           # Kubernetes client (existing)\n├── controller/                        # AR-007 (existing)\n├── gc/\n│   ├── gc_controller.go               # Main GC loop and coordination\n│   ├── gc_policy.go                   # TTL policy evaluation\n│   ├── gc_cleaner.go                  # Resource deletion logic\n│   ├── gc_metrics.go                  # Prometheus metrics\n│   ├── gc_config.go                   # Configuration defaults\n│   └── gc_test.go                     # Unit tests\n└── events/\n    ├── recorder.go                    # Event recording\n    └── events.go                      # Event types\n```\n\n### Configuration\n\nThe GC mechanism supports these configuration options:\n\n| Option | Type | Default | Description |\n|--------|------|---------|-------------|\n| enabled | bool | true | Enable/disable GC |\n| interval | duration | 5m | Scan interval |\n| defaultTTL | duration | 24h | Default TTL for sandboxes |\n| maxRetries | int | 3 | Cleanup retry attempts |\n| dryRun | bool | false | Preview cleanup without deletion |\n\n### Out-of-Scope\n- Real-time cleanup on CR deletion (handled by AR-007 finalizers)\n- Multi-cluster GC coordination (future enhancement)\n- Custom webhook for GC events (separate module)\n- Resource quota enforcement (separate feature)\n\n---\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n|------------|--------|---------|\n| github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go | local | Kubernetes typed client for listing resources |\n| github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/workloadmanager | local | Existing WorkloadManager |\n| github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1 | local | AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter types |\n| k8s.io/client-go/informers | ^0.34 | Cached list/watch for resources |\n| k8s.io/client-go/util/workqueue | ^0.34 | Rate-limited cleanup queue |\n\n### Upstream Dependencies\n\n- **AR-007 K8s Reconciler** — GC operates on resources created by the controller\n- **AR-005/AR-006 Sandbox Creation** — GC cleans up sandboxes from these APIs\n\n### Downstream Consumers\n\n1. **Kubernetes Cluster** — Reclaimed resources available for new workloads\n2. **Operators** — Reduced manual cleanup burden\n3. **Monitoring** — GC metrics for operational visibility\n4. **Compliance** — Automated data retention enforcement\n\n### Risks\n\n| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|------------|\n| Data loss | High | Dry-run mode, TTL defaults to 24h, configurable |\n| Resource conflicts | Medium | OwnerReference-based cleanup, finalizer coordination |\n| GC storms | Medium | Rate-limited queue, batch cleanup limits |\n| Clock skew | Low | Use monotonic clock for TTL calculations |\n| Incomplete cleanup | Medium | Retry logic with exponential backoff |\n\n---\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Option 1: TTL Controller with Lease Resources (Selected)\n\n**Approach**: Use Kubernetes Lease resources to track sandbox creation time, with a controller evaluating TTL and triggering cleanup.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Kubernetes-native pattern for TTL management\n- Leader-elected to prevent duplicate cleanup\n- Reuses existing informer infrastructure\n\n**Cons**:\n- Additional Lease resource per sandbox\n- Requires embedding creation timestamp\n\n**Decision**: Selected — provides reliable TTL tracking with K8s-native patterns.\n\n---\n\n### Option 2: TTL Annotations on CR\n\n**Approach**: Store TTL as an annotation on AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter CRs, evaluate during reconciliation.\n\n**Pros**:\n- No additional resources\n- Simple implementation\n\n**Cons**:\n- Tied to AR-007 reconciliation cycle (may delay cleanup)\n- Mixed concerns in reconciliation logic\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — couples GC to reconciliation, reducing independence and control.\n\n---\n\n### Option 3: External CronJob\n\n**Approach**: Deploy a CronJob that runs periodic cleanup scripts.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Simple deployment\n- No embedded controller code\n\n**Cons**:\n- No real-time response to resource changes\n- Limited visibility into cleanup status\n- Separate deployment and management\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — lacks integration with controller and real-time cleanup.\n\n---\n\n### Option 4: TTL Controller with Custom Resource\n\n**Approach**: Create a new `SandboxGC` CRD to define cleanup policies.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Declarative policy management\n- Multiple policies per namespace\n\n**Cons**:\n- Additional CRD complexity\n- Over-engineered for single-cluster use case\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — unnecessary API complexity for the current scope.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: GC Foundation\n- [ ] Add GC package to pkg/workloadmanager/gc/\n- [ ] Implement GC config with defaults and CLI flags\n- [ ] Create GC controller struct with client dependencies\n- [ ] Add informer factories for AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter\n\n### Phase 2: TTL Policy Engine\n- [ ] Implement TTL evaluation logic\n- [ ] Parse creationTimestamp from CR status\n- [ ] Handle edge cases (missing timestamp, future timestamps)\n- [ ] Add unit tests for TTL calculations\n\n### Phase 3: Resource Cleanup\n- [ ] Implement Pod cleanup with graceful period\n- [ ] Implement Service cleanup\n- [ ] Implement PVC cleanup with reclaim policy\n- [ ] Implement ConfigMap cleanup\n- [ ] Coordinate with AR-007 finalizers\n\n### Phase 4: GC Controller Loop\n- [ ] Implement periodic scan with configurable interval\n- [ ] Add workqueue for rate-limited cleanup\n- [ ] Implement retry logic with exponential backoff\n- [ ] Add leader election for HA\n\n### Phase 5: Observability\n- [ ] Add Prometheus metrics for GC operations\n- [ ] Record events for cleanup actions\n- [ ] Add logging for debugging\n\n### Phase 6: Testing\n- [ ] Unit tests for TTL policy evaluation\n- [ ] Mock tests for cleanup operations\n- [ ] Integration tests with mock API server\n- [ ] Dry-run mode validation\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] GC controller starts with configurable interval\n- [ ] Expired sandboxes are detected and cleaned up\n- [ ] All associated resources (Pod, Service, PVC, ConfigMap) are removed\n- [ ] GC respects namespace boundaries\n- [ ] Dry-run mode shows pending cleanups without deletion\n- [ ] Failed cleanups are retried with exponential backoff\n- [ ] Metrics accurately reflect GC operations\n- [ ] Events are recorded for cleanup actions\n- [ ] Unit tests pass with >60% coverage\n- [ ] GC integrates with AR-007 controller for consistent lifecycle","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md","exists":true,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775845986637,"end":1775845986667}}}}
